06684nam a22008895i 9783110716313DE-B159720230228015514.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107163137 a10.1515/97831107163132doi  a(DE-B1597)566973  a(OCoLC)1226680236  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0041902bisacsh00aReading Cicero's Final Years :bReceptions of the Post-Caesarian Works up to the Sixteenth Century - with two Epilogues /ced. by Christoph Pieper, Bram van der Velden. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (XIII, 298 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCICERO : Studies on Roman Thought and Its Reception ,x2567-0158 ;v300tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tTable of Contents -- tSummary of the Chapters -- tIntroduction -- tWere Cicero's Philippics the Cause of his Death? -- tThe Thrill of Defeat -- tIlle regit dictis animos -- tMan of Peace? -- tLibera uoluntas -- tCiceronian Reception in the Epistula ad Octauianum -- tCan it Ever be Wise to Kill the Tyrant? -- tBruni, Cicero, and their Manifesto for Republicanism -- tMultilayered Appropriation(s) -- tMarc-Antoine Muret and his Lectures on Cicero's De officiis -- tFirst Epilogue -- tSecond Epilogue -- tBibliography -- tIndex Locorum -- tIndex Nominum0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThis volume contributes to the ongoing scholarly debate regarding the reception of Cicero. It focuses on one particular moment in Cicero's life, the period from the death of Caesar up to Cicero's own death. These final years have shaped Cicero's reception in an special way, as they have condensed and enlarged themes that his life stands for: on the positive side his fight for freedom and the republic against mighty opponents (for which he would finally be killed); on the other hand his inconsistency in terms of political alliances and tendency to overestimate his own influence. For that reason, many later readers viewed the final months of Cicero's life as his swan song, and as representing the essence of his life as a whole.The fixed scope of this volume facilitates an analysis of the underlying debates about the historical character Cicero and his textual legacy (speeches, letters and philosophical works) through the ages, stretching from antiquity itself to the present day. Major themes negotiated in this volume are the influence of Cicero's regular attempts to anticipate his later reception; the question of whether or not Cicero showed consistency in his behaviour; his debatable heroism with regard to republican freedom; and the interaction between philosophy, rhetoric and politics.  aIssued also in print.  afunded by Patrum Lumen Sustine-Stiftung (PLuS)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aCicero. 4aRezeptionsstudien. 4aRömische Republik. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aCicero.  aEnd of the Roman Republic.  aReception Studies.1 aBishop, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDel Giovane, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJansen, Leanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeeline, Thomas J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLa Bua, Giuseppe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMabboux, Carole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManuwald, Gesine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a